According to Eq. 5, the percentage of α-helix content of HHb has been calculated and % α-helicity is observed to decrease by only 1.4% at 209 nm in presence of GO (Table 4A
                        ). Likewise according to eq. 6, the % of α–helicity decrease by only 0.5% at 220 nm upon interaction with GO(Table 4B
                        ). However, the percentage of α-helicity of HHb as calculated from Eq. (5) appears to increase by only 1.1% 209 nm upon addition of RGO(Table 4A). Similarlyaccording to eq. 6, the % of α–helix content, increases by only 0.55% at 220 nm in presence of RGO(Table 4B). Thus in spite of the interaction between HHb and GO/RGO, the CD spectra of HHb remains almost unchanged although minute changes in the values of mean residue ellipticity (MRE), θ, has been noticed. The above observation thus suggests maintenance of the overall secondary structure by retaining its α–helix content in presence of GO/RGO. All in all the systematic efforts reveal the capability of GO and RGO in biological microenvironment particularly for biomedical application like drug delivery system, development of biosensorsand others.
